Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2 — Intercept hardware/software back and show a dialog:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` in your page code-behind:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Fire-and-forget the async dialog; return true to cancel navigation now
            ConfirmDiscardAsync();
            return true; // cancels the back navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed(); // allows normal navigation
    }

    private async Task ConfirmDiscardAsync()
    {
        bool discard = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (discard)
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

> **Note:** `OnBackButtonPressed` handles the **Android hardware back button** and the **Shell back arrow**. Return `true` to cancel navigation.

**3 — Custom "Cancel" back button:**

In your XAML, use `BackButtonBehavior`:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your view-model (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand CancelCommand => new Command(async () =>
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
});
```

**Key points:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` guards the system back gesture/button.
- `BackButtonBehavior` with `Command` replaces the Shell back arrow tap, so your `CancelCommand` handles that path.
- Both paths funnel through the same confirmation logic before calling `GoToAsync("..")`.
